name: Tempura Flour (Batter)
description: Tempura is a Japanese dish where various vegetables and seafood are deep fried in a very light, iced batter. Tempura is different to other fried foods as the batter is often chilled before being used to give an extremely delicate crunch that feels much healthier than normal deep fried foods.

name: Panko Bread Crumbs
description: Panko is a type of flaky breadcrumb. It’s commonly used in Asian cuisine, although it has become more popular and widely available in Western cooking. Panko has a light, airy, and delicate texture that helps it crisp as it cooks. It can be used as a crunchy topping to add texture to baked casseroles, like macaroni and cheese, as a breaded coating for fried foods, or as a binder for meatballs.

name: Gwa Pao
description: Gwa pao, also known as steamed bao, Taiwanese Hamburger, pork bellow buns, or ambiguously, bao, is a xiaochi dish originating from Fuzhou with similar variants found across China, and a popular Taiwanese street food.

name: Yuzu Mayo
description: All natural and loaded with Yuzu, Hotaru Yuzu Mayo is a traditional Japanese Mayonnaise, meaning it is dense, firm, rich and luxurious. This is achieved by using high in acidity Yuzu Fruit as the acidifier and tons of eggs compared to the common Mayonnaise. This yields a style that is preferred by accomplished chefs.

name: Yuzu Marmalade
description: Tart and sweet with a tinge of bitterness made from Yuzu fruit, sugar and honey. We love a dollop of this slathered on a slice of toasted dark bread. Try stirring a bit into a pan sauce for duck or pork. Whisk a spoonful into a dressing for a green salad or ceviche with fresh herbs. Spoon over ice cream or sorbet. Use a base for a tart with almond paste and fresh citrus.

name: Pink Sushi Ginger
description: Thinly sliced ginger that has been marinated in a solution of water and vinegar. Often served and eaten after sushi, and is sometimes called sushi ginger. It is considered to be essential in the presentation of sushi. It is used to cleanse the palate between eating different pieces of sushi, or alternatively before or after the meal.

name: Green Yuzu Koshu
description: A classic table condiment found throughout Japan, Yakami Orchards Yuzu Kosho has become a secred ingredient of America’s finest chefs. Fresh Yuzu Zest is combined with Fresh Chilies, Sea Salt and Konbu Seaweed to create a bright, spicy flavor profile with a subtle Umami finish. Incredible as a rub on meat and poultry, a wonderful condiment with sush, add a dab to marinades, salad dressings, soups or eggs, or even toss with pasta. A must try for any Japanese cuisine enthusiast.

name: Lychee in Syrup
description: Lychees are brightly colored strawberry shaped fruits with thin large skin and sweet musky aroma. The native Thai fruit, lychees are walnut sized succulent and juicy white fruit. Lychees are delicious with ice cream or in a fruity signature cocktail.

name: Edamame Unpeeled
description: Edamame are young soy beans still in the pod, unpeeled. Because the beans are young and green when they are picked, edamame soybeans are soft and edible.

name: Dried Wasabi Peas
description: Wasabi peas are green peas that have been roasted and coated in a mixture of starch, sugar, salt, oil and wasabi. Wasabi peas are actually both salty, spicy and bursting with bold flavor. Eat wasabi peas in moderation, as they are extremely high in protein, along with following a healthy diet. Once rehydrated add wasabi peas into soups, wraps and even trail mix.

name: Yuzu Juice Unpasteurized
description: It’s incredibly fragrant, but also super sour and tart, which means it’s not meant to be eaten as is. Instead, its zest and juice are used for flavoring in the kitchen. The flavors of sour orange, lemon and tangerine are great for salad dressings, cocktails and a dipping sauce or marinade.

name: Sudachi Juice Unpasteurized
description: Desired by the world’s finest chefs and mixologists, Yakami Orchard Sudachi Juice, is a first press using the whole fruit, capturing the intense floral aroma and tart, peppery flavor qualitites of ripe Sudachi Fruit. Sudachi Juice is a rare and vibrant ingredient perfect for cocktails and non-alcoholic drinks, vinaigrettes, ceviche, sauces and desserts or whenever a splash of fresh Sudachi Citrus will create the flavor complexity you desire in whatever creation demands the best.

name: Coconut Milk
description: Coconut milk is the liquid that comes from the grated meat of a mature coconut. The opacity and rich taste of coconut milk are attributed to its high oil content, most of which is saturated fat. Coconut milk is a popular food ingredient used in Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, and northern South America. Coconut milk can be used as a lactose-free, vegan milk substitute in countless capacities, use it as a healthier yet sweet tasting alternative to animal dairy products.

name: Thai Yellow Curry Paste
description: Yellow Curry paste is another curry flavor that you may want to try. The yellow color comes from tumeric, one of the key ingredients. Other ingredients include: lemon grass, garlic, shallots, salt, galangal, dried red chilli, coriander seed, kaffir lime peel, cumin, cinnamon, mace, tumeric, and cardamon. Yellow curry paste is so versatile, you’ll want to try it with a variety of meat, seafood, vegetable, noodle, and even soup recipes.

name: Thai Red Curry Paste
description: Red Curry Paste gets its color from the red chillis which are ground together with other ingredients as well as shrimp paste. It is a very hot curry, although it is sweeter than the other curries, it’s in the range such as red or yellow. It also contains lemongrass, garlic, salt, shallots, and galangal. Red curry is a popular Thai dish consisting of red curry paste cooked in coconut milk and added with meat such as chicken, beef, pork, duck or shrimp, or vegetarian protein source such as tofu.

name: Thai Green Curry Paste
description: Green Curry Paste gets its color from the green chillis which are ground together with the other ingredients as well as shrimp paste. It is a very hot curry, as it is the base for the typical Thai green curry, although it is sweeter than the other curries it ranges from red or yellow. It also contains lemongrass, garlic, salt, shallots, and galangal. Add to your favorite meats or seafood, noodles, vegetables, tofu, or wheat gluten, this paste will create sumptuous curries.

name: Tahini Paste
description: Tahini is a paste made from ground sesame seeds. Tahini is one of the main ingredients in Middle Eastern dishes like hummus and babaganoush. It makes a wonderful base for salad dressings and adds great nutritional value and texture to smoothies. Spread on whole grain toast with a little bit of miso paste it makes a great addition to a savory sandwich.

name: Harissa Paste
description: Inherited from Northern African culture, Harissa is a must have to cook any Moroccan or Tunisian meal such as couscous. Used as a black pepper, it seasons and personalizes your meals, thanks to its prestigious taste.

name: Harissa Paste
description: Harissa is a spicy and aromatic chile paste that’s a widely used staple in North African and Middle Eastern cooking. This paste is made from chilli peppers and other spices. Even if you love spicy food, harissa packs quite a punch, a little goes a long way.

name: Harissa
description: This deeply fiery and aromatic pepper spread is a classic North African condiment often used to enhance soups, stews, grilled meats or greens and grain salads.

name: Green Harissa
description: A fiery, lively, herbaceous Harissa crafted from green chili peppers, herbs and spices. A wonderful addition to stir-frys, roasted veggies or grilled meat.

name: Wasabi Powder
description: Wasabi, known as Japanese horseradish, is used as a spice and has an extremely strong flavor. This product is true wasabi, while evocative of common horseradish, is actually more subtle and complex.
extra_data: {"caseCount":"Shelf Stable","shelfstable":"Store in a Cool Dry Pantry","origin":""}

name: Chinese Five Spice Powder
description: Five spice may be used with fatty meats such as pork, duck or goose. It is used as a spice rub for chicken, duck, pork and seafood, in red cooking recipes, or added to the breading for fried foods. Contains anniseed, fennel, citrus peel, cinnamon and ginger.

name: Thin Soy Sauce
description: Thin soy sauce imported from Thailand. 50% soybean, 50% wheat flour.

name: Teriyaki Sauce
description: Use it for your next stir-fry, dip grilled meats in it too, or drizzle it on a burger, or dip appetizers in it! This versatile sauce is as easy as it is delicious. This is a simple mixture of soy sauce, brown sugar, Sake, and mirin, cooked down until it becomes a semi-thick, spoon-coating sauce with a constant pull between sweet and salty.

name: Tamari White Soy Sauce
description: Complex aromas of earthy must, leather, fermented soy beans and White Pepper are present on the nose while flavor notes of Savory, Umami, Fungal and hints of Pine fill the palate. Used in Japan as a finishing Shoyu or as a stand-alone ingredient, Haku Matsutake Shoyu stands out among Japan s great Shoyus.

name: Tamari Soy Sauce
description: Tamari is a wider class of soy sauces, and is made with no or very little wheat, while traditional soy sauce does contain wheat. It can be used in asian and non-asian cooking to add a full, savory, umami flavor to your dishes.

name: Sweet Soy Sauce
description: Sweet soy sauce is an Indonesian sweetened aromatic soy sauce, which has a dark colour, a thick syrupy consistency and a unique, pronounced, sweet and somewhat molasses-like flavor due to the generous addition of palm sugar.

name: Sriracha Sauce
description: Sriracha is made from sun-ripen chilies which are ground into a smooth paste along with garlic. It is excellent in soups, sauces, pastas, pizzas, hot dogs, hamburgers, chow mien or on anything else to give it a delicious, spicy taste.
extra_data: {"caseCount":12,"shelfstable":"Store in a dry cool place","origin":"Spicy and savory"}

name: Plum Sauce
description: Koon Chun plum sauce is a sweet and sour sauce which is made from selected plums, chilies, and ginger. It is the most popular sauce for dipping “roast goose” and grilled or roasted meats. It is also widely used in marinated and stir-fried dishes. It is a delicious, authentic plum sauce.

name: Oyster Sauce
description: Bottled oyster-flavored sauce is a rich, concentrated mixture of oyster extractives, soy sauce, brine and assorted seasonings. The brown sauce is thick, salty, and strong. It is used sparingly to enhance the flavor of many dishes that have a long list of additional wet and aromatic ingredients. Often used in broccli beef.

name: Mushroom Soy Sauce
description: Dark soy sauce is used throughout Asia and is a bit richer and thicker than the lighter varieties. It tends to have a chocolate brown color, and a pungent, rather than overly salty, flavor. Mushroom soy sauce is a dark soy sauce from China which adds straw mushroom essence to the sauce’s brew.
extra_data: {"caseCount":12,"shelfstable":"Store in a cool place. Refrigerate after opening.","origin":"Thailand"}

name: Mirin Wine
description: Mirin is a common staple used in Japanese cooking. It’s a type of rice wine, similar to sake, but with a lower alcohol and higher sugar content. Mirin has a sweet flavor, which makes it a nice contrast when used with saltier sauces, like soy or tamari. It has a golden to light amber color and a slightly thick consistency. Mirin is also known for toning down dishes that have a strong fishy or gamey taste. Do note that mirin has a strong, distinct taste, so use it in small quantities. A little goes a long way.

name: Japanese Ponzu
description: A citrus-based sauce commonly used in Japanese cuisine. It is tart, with a thin, watery consistency and a dark brown color. It’s a great dipping sauce for cold noodles, salads, dumplings, grilled meats and fish, cold sliced meat or fish, or any number of other dishes.

name: Hot Chili Oil
description: Condiment made from vegetable oil that has been infused with chili peppers. It is commonly used in Chinese cuisine, East and Southeast Asia and elsewhere. Particularly popular in Sichuan cuisine, it is used as an ingredient in cooked dishes as well as a condiment.

name: Hoisin Sauce
description: Hoisin sauce is a thick, pungent sauce commonly used in Chinese cuisine as a glaze for meat, an addition to stir fries, or as dipping sauce. It is darkly colored in appearance and sweet and salty in taste. This Hoisin sauce is soy-based and made up of soybean paste, garlic, vinegar, red chillies, and other spices.

name: Fish Sauce
description: Fish sauce is a condiment made from fish coated in salt and fermented from weeks to up to two years. A strong fermented fish flavor sauce, dark in color.

name: Chili Garlic Sauce
description: A spicy red chili sauce with garlic overtones

name: Char Siu Sauce
description: Used in variously in different Asian cultures due to it’s darkbrown and viscious sauce. Consists of sugar, water, salt, honey and fermented soybean paste. The sweet fermented soy bean flavor compliments most dishes and meats.

name: Black Garlic Shoyu
description: Haku Black Garlic Shoyu is a truly extraordinary expression of the progessive next generation, complex aromas of earthy must and fermented soy beans are present. With notes of fig, raisin, molasses, and fermented garlic, this soy sauce is perfect for making a rich vinaigrette or tatsuta age. Also great as a dipping sauce for lamb or as an ingredient in vegetable stir fry.

name: White Sesame Seeds
description: Sesame seeds are tiny, flat oval seeds with a nutty taste and a delicate, almost invisible crunch. They come in a host of different colors. Sesame seeds are highly valued for their high content of sesame oil, an oil that is very resistant to rancidity. Sesame seeds are the main ingredients in both tahini and the Middle Eastern sweet treat, halvah.

name: Wasabi Sesame Seeds
description: Wasabi Sesame Seeds are small sesame seeds with an earthy green color. They have a prominent rich and nutty sesame flavor with spicy wasabi undertones.
extra_data: {"caseCount":"Shelf Stable","shelfstable":"Store in a Cool Dry Pantry","origin":""}

name: Soy Sesame Seeds
description: These seeds have a sesame nutty flavor with soy sauce undertones.

name: Bamboo Charcoal Spicy Sesame Seeds
description: Bamboo Charcoal Spicy Sesame Seeds are small with an earthy black color. They have a prominent rich and nutty sesame flavor with smoky charcoal understones. These special sesame seeds add a delicious taste and brilliant color to any dish for a quick fusion of Asian flavor.

name: Wakame Dried Seaweed
description: It has a subtly sweet flavor and is most often served in soups and salads. Wakame seaweed is one of the healthiest Japanese foods due to being rich in vitamins & minerals.

name: Roasted Nori Sheets
description: Nori is the Japanese name for vaious edible seaweed species, also known as seaweed wrap for sushi. Crips and delicious sheets of roasted seafood essential to the fabrication of sushi. It is also a garnish or flavoring in noodle preparations and soups. Can also be eaten by being made into a soy sauce paste.

name: Frozen Seaweed Salad
description: Sea vegetables are virtually fat-free, low calorie and are one of the richest sources of minerals in the vegetable kingdom. A healthy blend of seaweeds, creating the perfect Asian salad, simply thaw and serve. Contains no MSG.

name: Dried Kelp
description: Kombu is a kind of sea cabbage, otherwise known as seaweed. It is a natural flavor enhancer that offers huge health benefits for its tiny size. Good source of dietary fiber. Goes well with just about anything and brings out the true flavor from the other foods.

name: Togarashi Spice
description: Togarashi has a special affinity for Japanese noodles and soups, but can also perk up fish, poultry and beef. We love it on spinach sautéed in a touch of sesame oil. Contains Chinese chile, orange peel, seaweed, ginger, poppy seeds, and sesame seeds.

name: Katsuobushi – Bonito
description: Katsuobushi, or Skipjack Tuna is filleted into 4 loins, simmered for a couple of hours, deboned, rubbed with fish paste and then smoked for about a month. Each loin is then elegantly shaved down to create a perfect shape and is sprayed with a mold similar to Koji. The finished loins spend the next 6 months cycling between the humid fermentation room and the dry sunlight. Katsuobushi is a fundamental and critical ingredient across all Japanese cuisine. It can be found in soup stocks, salads, dipping sauces, marinades, rice dishes, sushi and often a garnish.

name: Furikak Seto
description: It typically consists of a mixture of dried fish, sesame seeds, chopped seaweed, sugar and salt. A dry Japanese seasoning that can be sprinkled on top of cooked rice, vegetables, and fish. Brightly colored and flaky.

name: Tapioca Pearls – Small
description: Tapioca pearls come from tapioca, which is a starch extracted from the cassava root. It is used as a thickening agent in many foods. mostly used in Boba Tea, tapioca pudding, and other various desserts.

name: Tapioca Pearls – Large
description: Tapioca pearls come from tapioca, which is a starch extracted from the cassava root. It is used as a thickening agent in many foods. mostly used in Boba Tea, tapioca pudding, and other various desserts.

name: Vinegar Ginsho Sushi
description: Sushi Seasoning is a mixture of vinegar, sweetener and salt brewed in a slow and natural process that is centuries old. Great for making sushi rice, salad dressings or marinades. When mixed with warm rice it adds the characteristic sheen and flavor ofine sushi rice. The combination of the vinegar’s mild tartness and sweetness of sugar make it a delightfully simple salad dressing.

name: Ume-Shiso Vinegar
description: Su Ume Shiso Vinegar is a result of a one and half year aged brine and possesses a nice firm fruity taste with the natural sweetness of the process. The marriage of perfectly ripe fruit and the timing of the addition of the Red Shiso leaves, along with age is what creates this wonderful, unique vinegar. Umesu is a sweet vinegar and it best when used in moderation to lift flavors and excite palates.

name: Ginger Vinegar
description: Master crafted by true vinegar artisans following ancestral methods handed down through the generations, Togo Su Ginger Vinegar is the perfect combination of spice, acidity and the natural floral bouquet only ginger can provide. Created by natural fermentation. The finished product is a perfect balance of spice, nice acidity, and pleasant ginger bouquet, lending many culinary applications.

name: Yellow Soy Wrapper
description: Soft yellow soy wrappers colored yellow add a festive pop of color to any dish. Create imaginative sushi, sandwich wraps, appetizers and desserts. These healthy wrappers are made from natural ingredients, with no saturated fat, trans fat or cholesterol and are very low in carbohydrates and sodium.

name: Won Ton Wrappers
description: Not just for won tons, these paper-thin sheets of dough can be fried or baked, then filled and served as an appetizer or dessert. Great for making Asian appetizers, dumplings and other dishes.

name: Spring Roll Wrapper
description: Tee Yih spring roll wrappers.

name: Rice Paper
description: Edible rice paper is used for making fresh summer rolls (salad rolls) or fried spring rolls Vietnamese cuisine. Ingredients of the food rice paper include white rice flour, tapioca flour,salt, and water. Rice paper is sold in dried sheets. Before using them, you will need to rehydrate them to make them pliable.

name: Pink Soy Wrapper
description: Soft pink soy wrapper colored pink to add a festive pop of color to any dish. Create imaginative sushi, sandwich wraps, appetizers and desserts. These healthy wrappers are made from natural ingredients, with no saturated fat, trans fat or cholesterol and are very low in carbohydrates and sodium.

These healthy wrappers are made from natural ingredients, with no saturated fat, trans fat or cholesterol and are very low in carbohydrates and sodium.

name: Gyoza Wrapper
description: Gyoza wrappers, also known as won ton wrappers, are generally thicker than won ton skins, and are especially well-suited to frying. They are thin sheets, 3 1/2″ round, of dough made with wheat flour and water.

name: Green Soy Wrapper
description: Soft green soy wrappers colored green to add a festive pop of color to any dish. Create imaginative sushi, sandwich wraps, appetizers and desserts. These healthy wrappers are made from natural ingredients, with no saturated fat, trans fat or cholesterol and are very low in carbohydrates and sodium.

name: Egg Roll Wrappers
description: Thick pastry egg roll wrappers can be used for a wide range of culinary applications. Not just for egg rolls these paper-thin sheets of dough can be fried or baked, then filled and served as an appetizer, snack, or dessert.

name: Banana Leaves
description: Banana leaves are large, flexible, and waterproof. They impart an aroma to food that is cooked in or served on them, steaming with banana leaves imparts a subtle sweet flavor and aroma to the dish. Banana leaves are utlized in much the same way Americans use aluminium foil, the leaves are not themselves eaten and are discarded after the contents are consumed. Fish, vegetables, rice can all be gently steamed inside a banana leaf parcel.

name: Somen Noodles
description: Usually served cold, Somen Noodles are very thin white noodles made of wheat flour. Serve with a lightly flavored dipping sauce.

name: Pad Thai Noodles
description: Rice noodles are noodles that are made from rice flour and water. Sometimes referred to as pad thai noodles, these medium-sized flat rice noodles are known as sen lek in Thailand. Used mostly in Pad Thai dishes.

name: Lo-Mein/Canton Noodles
description: Lo-Mien/Canton Noodles made in the USA. Noodles are dry, made from several high-quality pasta ingredients. Very little color and preservatives are used and last over 6 months. Cooks and absorbs water without bloating and sogginess. Maintains a high al-dente or chewy texture, and when noodles are cooked in hot water will not exhibit any splitting.

name: Lo Mein Noodles
description: Made from boiled wheat noodles. Great with stir fried vegetables, meats, and sauce.
extra_data: {"caseCount":"Shelf Stable","shelfstable":"Store in a Cool Dry Pantry","origin":""}

name: Green Tea Soba Noodles
description: Made with premium Green tea, the Cha Soba has a wonderful fresh earthiness flavor with hints of wheat grass. Crafted following multi-century old traditions handed down through the generations. Just the right amount of gluten to provide the ideal chewiness and texture.

name: Chuka Soba Noodles
description: Chuka soba are the Japanese version of Chinese egg noodles. They’re curly, made with wheat flour, have a mild flavor and a fine texture. Packaged in brick form Chuka Soba noodles are not fried in oil as ramen noodles are before they are dried. Chuka soba noodles cook quickly and are often used in soups, main dishes and stir-fried dishes.

name: Cellophane Noodles
description: Cellophan noodles are extremely thin translucent noodles used extensively in Asian cuisine, such as soups, stir fried dishes, or spring rolls. They are called cellophane noodles or glass noodles because of their appearance when cooked, resembling cellophane, a clear material of a translucent light gray or brownish-gray color.

name: Buckwheat Soba Noodles
description: Buckwheat is the second most harvest crop in Japan, making it a foundational ingredient through the cuisine. Just the right amount of gluten to provide the ideal chewiness and texture. Serve hor or cold, in a dashi broth or dip in a kaeshi sauce.

name: Yuzu Miso Paste
description: Namikura Yuzu Miso is a tradtional lighter style miso that is fermented with hearty chunks of yuzu fruit and yuzu zest. This miso is aged 3 months which allows the floral aroma and bright, semi-tart yuzu flavor to stand out. Yuzu Miso is an exciting, versatile miso that can be used across a multitude of cuisines and applications. Namikura Miso Co is a family-owned 5th generation producer that is highly regarded throughout Japan for its incredible depth and flavor and superb texture.

name: White Miso Paste
description: This miso is made from soybeans that have been fermented with a large percentage of rice mixed with salt. The actual resulting color can range from white to light beige, and the miso has a definite sweet taste. The typical thick paste used for sauces, pickling vegetables or meats, and mixing with dashi soup stock to serve as miso soup Misoshiru.It’s best used in condiments like mayo or salad dressings, or in light sauces.

name: Shrimp Paste (not Base)
description: It is primarily made from finely crushed shrimp or krill mixed with salt, and then fermented for several weeks. Shrimp paste or shrimp sauce is a fermented condiment that yields a very distinctive taste, commonly used in Southeast Asian, Northeastern South Asian and Southern Chinese cuisines. Outside of taste shrimp paste also adds protein to dishes and can be used in many currys and salads.

name: Sambal Oelek Chili Paste
description: A full bodied sauce with the pure taste of chilies, this paste is red in color. No other flavors have been added for those who prefer a simpler taste, adding just the right amount of heat to give food a flavorful boost. Add ground fresh chili paste to make any food mouth-warmingly spicy. Use it to heat up your stir-fry dishes, pizza, eggs, pasta, or anything you desire. Made in USA with California produce.

name: Red Miso Paste
description: Miso is a traditional Japanese food produced by fermenting rice, barley and/or soybeans, with salt and the mold kojikin. It can range in color from red to dark brown. The typical thick paste and deep umami flavor of red miso can overwhelm mild dishes, but is perfect for sauces, pickling vegetables or meats, hearty soups, braises, and glazes. Miso pastes can be used for marinades, one of the most popular recipes currently being the Black Cod Miso made famous by Nobu.

name: Red Miso
description: Namikura Aka (Red) miso is classified as a red miso due to being aged for at least 6 months and also by using less rice and more soybeans in its production. The longer miso ages, the darker and stronger it becomes. Namikura Miso Co is a family-owned, 5th generation producer that is highly regarded throughout Japan for its incredible depth of flavor and superb texture.

name: Namikura White Miso Paste
description: Kyoto Shiro miso is typically made with 1.5 to 2 times as much white rice koji as cooked soybeans and lower salt ratio than other miso. It is known for its lighter color, smooth texture and milder flavor and is often thinned with sake and spread on fish to marinate prior to grilling.

name: Chu Hou Paste
description: Made from quality soybeans, garlic, ginger and sesame seeds. This convenient cooking ingredient is specially designed for braising meats and vegetables.
